g agencies win more pitches and proposals?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. Agencies use AI to accelerate pitch research, generate first-draft strategy decks, and personalize proposals at scale. The highest-leverage use is loading a prospect's brand, competitors, and category into a Claude Project and generating a situational analysis in minutes rather than hours. This expands the number of pitches an agency can pursue without adding headcount."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What AI tools do marketing agencies use for client reporting?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Agencies use three approaches: DIY reporting built with Claude plus data connectors (lowest cost, most customizable), dedicated platforms like Whatagraph or Insightful ($200 to $800/mo, faster setup), or Looker Studio with AI-written narrative summaries. The DIY approach works well for agencies with 5 to 15 clients; dedicated platforms pay off at 20 or more clients where reporting time compounds."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How should marketing agencies price engagements when using AI tools?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Agencies that adopt AI should price on strategy and outcomes rather than hours, not cut rates proportionally. AI-enabled agencies can deliver 2 to 3 times the output for the same retainer, which expands margins rather than reducing prices. Package AI capabilities into tiered retainers: a strategic tier includes the AI content and research engine, while a standard tier covers execution only. Agencies that compete on AI-lowered prices commodity themselves."}}]}</script>
